<paragraph blockId="7.[151,607,223,250]" box="[151,607,223,250]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,607,223,250]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,607,223,250]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">
Synonymy of 
<taxonomicName authority="Causey, 1958" authorityName="Causey" authorityYear="1958" box="[322,607,223,250]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Vaferaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[322,436,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">Vaferaria</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Causey, N. B." box="[444,607,223,250]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" pagination="179 - 184" refId="ref10808" refString="Causey, N. B. (1958) New records and descriptions of a new genus and a new species of millipeds of the family Striariidae (Chordeumida). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 71, 179 - 184." type="journal article" year="1958">Causey, 1958</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="282" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,293,1325]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">
<bibRefCitation author="Loomis, H. F." box="[151,321,293,320]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" pagination="404 - 409" refId="ref11257" refString="Loomis, H. F. (1936) New millipeds of the American family Striariidae. Journal of the Washington Academy of Science, 26, 404 - 409." type="journal article" year="1936">Loomis (1936)</bibRefCitation>
surveyed the known striariids, and added two new species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loomis" authorityYear="1936" box="[1021,1174,293,319]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Striaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nana">
<emphasis box="[1021,1174,293,319]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">Striaria nana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[1234,1437,293,319]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loomis" authorityYear="1936" box="[1234,1433,293,319]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Striaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imberbis">Striaria imberbis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The latter species, according to Loomis, had characters that were not found in other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bollman" authorityYear="1888" box="[1099,1186,328,354]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Striaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1099,1186,328,354]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">Striaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, including the dorsum of the rings, which was said to be “depressed throughout, but [on] the anterior ones more strikingly so.” Additionally, the single male 
<typeStatus box="[444,542,397,423]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">holotype</typeStatus>
appeared to lack the sinuate spines on the angles of the labrum, had prominently expanded lateralmost crests (the sixth) on the second ring, and prominent lobes on the trochanters of the second legs. Loomis only provided drawings of a second leg. Much later, 
<bibRefCitation author="Causey, N. B." box="[917,1083,465,492]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" pagination="179 - 184" refId="ref10808" refString="Causey, N. B. (1958) New records and descriptions of a new genus and a new species of millipeds of the family Striariidae (Chordeumida). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 71, 179 - 184." type="journal article" year="1958">Causey (1958)</bibRefCitation>
cited some of these characters (still unillustrated) and named a new genus, 
<emphasis box="[656,769,501,527]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">
<taxonomicName authority="Causey, 1958" authorityName="Causey" authorityYear="1958" box="[656,765,501,527]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Vaferaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Vaferaria</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
for 
<emphasis box="[818,952,501,527]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loomis" authorityYear="1936" box="[818,948,501,527]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Striaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imberbis">S. imberbis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
emphasizing especially the “flattening” of the anterior rings. It is not clear from her description that she actually studied the 
<typeStatus box="[1075,1173,535,561]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis box="[1212,1346,536,562]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loomis" authorityYear="1936" box="[1212,1342,536,562]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Striaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imberbis">S. imberbis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Indeed, it appears that no mature male specimens of any of the species discussed (except possibly for 
<emphasis box="[1210,1359,570,597]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bollman" authorityYear="1888" box="[1210,1354,570,597]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Striaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granulosa">S. granulosa</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and in that case not the types) were examined. 
<bibRefCitation author="Hoffman, R. L." box="[595,770,605,631]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" refId="ref11201" refString="Hoffman, R. L. (1979) Classification of the Diplopoda. Museum d'Histoire Naturelle, Geneve, 237 pp." type="book" year="1979">Hoffman (1979</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Hoffman, R. L." box="[781,838,605,631]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" pagination="1 - 584" refId="ref11224" refString="Hoffman, R. L. (1999) Checklist of the millipeds of North and Middle America. Virginia Museum of Natural History Special Publications, 8, 1 - 584." type="journal article" year="1999">1999</bibRefCitation>
) persistently misspelled the genus name as “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Causey" authorityYear="1958" box="[1336,1417,605,631]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Vaferia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1336,1417,605,631]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">Vaferia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
,” and 
<bibRefCitation author="Shear, W. A. &amp; Krejca, J. K." box="[199,455,639,666]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" pagination="23 - 39" refId="ref11524" refString="Shear, W. A. &amp; Krejca, J. K. (2007) Revalidation of the millipede genus Amplaria Chamberlin 1941 (Diplopoda, Chordeumatida, Striariidae) and description of two new species from caves in Sequoia and Kings Canyon National Parks, California. Zootaxa, 1532 (1), 23 - 39. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1532.1.2" type="journal article" year="2007">Shear &amp; Krejca (2007)</bibRefCitation>
made the same mistake.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,293,1325]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">
As a part of a survey of the described species of 
<emphasis box="[736,830,675,701]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bollman" authorityYear="1888" box="[736,826,675,701]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Striaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Striaria</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
I studied the 
<typeStatus box="[980,1078,674,700]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">holotype</typeStatus>
and only known male specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loomis" authorityYear="1936" box="[181,307,709,735]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Striaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imberbis">
<emphasis box="[181,307,709,735]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">S. imberbis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Smithsonian National Museum of Natural History); collected south of Atascadero, San Luis Obispo Co., 
<collectingRegion box="[207,323,743,769]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">California</collectingRegion>
, by O. F. Cook, 
<date box="[517,695,744,770]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" value="1928-01-01">1 January 1928</date>
, along with a female and “a number of young”, unfortunately in rather poor condition. The gonopods had not been dissected. While the shelf-like sixth crest of the second segment, the lack of a labral spine, and the presence of large lobes on the second leg trochanters all proved to be repeatable observations, the “flattening” of the body, even anteriorly, was not. The structure of the rings was typical of other striariids, and it remains unclear what exactly Loomis meant in his description by “depressed,” though he may have been referring to the median sulcus, deeply infolded in species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bollman" authorityYear="1888" box="[907,994,917,943]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Striaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[907,994,917,943]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">Striaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. I dissected and studied the gonopods, ninth legs and second legs at high magnification under the compound microscope (
<figureCitation box="[1080,1216,951,978]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–14" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1872,1897]" captionTargetBox="[154,1323,153,1811]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1373,151,1855]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 9–14. Striaria columbiana and Amplaria imberbis. Figs. 9, 10. Striaria columbiana. Fig. 9. Left gonopod, mesal view; pcc, posterior lobe of colpocoxite; other labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 10. Right gonopod, lateral view; labels as in Fig. 9. Figs. 11–14. Amplaria imberbis male holotype. Fig. 11. Right gonopod, lateral view; labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 12. Angiocoxite tips of right gonopod, mesal view; labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 13. Legpair 9 of male, anterior view; cp, coxal pore; other labels as in Fig. 8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734462" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734462/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">Figs. 11–14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,293,1325]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">
I found that the gonopods (
<figureCitation box="[507,642,986,1012]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–14" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1872,1897]" captionTargetBox="[154,1323,153,1811]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1373,151,1855]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 9–14. Striaria columbiana and Amplaria imberbis. Figs. 9, 10. Striaria columbiana. Fig. 9. Left gonopod, mesal view; pcc, posterior lobe of colpocoxite; other labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 10. Right gonopod, lateral view; labels as in Fig. 9. Figs. 11–14. Amplaria imberbis male holotype. Fig. 11. Right gonopod, lateral view; labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 12. Angiocoxite tips of right gonopod, mesal view; labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 13. Legpair 9 of male, anterior view; cp, coxal pore; other labels as in Fig. 8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734462" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734462/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">Figs. 11, 12</figureCitation>
) and ninth legs (
<figureCitation box="[834,917,986,1012]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–14" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1872,1897]" captionTargetBox="[154,1323,153,1811]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1373,151,1855]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 9–14. Striaria columbiana and Amplaria imberbis. Figs. 9, 10. Striaria columbiana. Fig. 9. Left gonopod, mesal view; pcc, posterior lobe of colpocoxite; other labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 10. Right gonopod, lateral view; labels as in Fig. 9. Figs. 11–14. Amplaria imberbis male holotype. Fig. 11. Right gonopod, lateral view; labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 12. Angiocoxite tips of right gonopod, mesal view; labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 13. Legpair 9 of male, anterior view; cp, coxal pore; other labels as in Fig. 8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734462" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734462/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
), while in some ways simple, were consistent with the striariid species now assigned to a revalidated 
<taxonomicName authority="Chamberlin, 1941" authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1941" box="[763,1076,1021,1047]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Amplaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[763,869,1021,1047]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">Amplaria</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Chamberlin, R. V." box="[875,1076,1021,1047]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" pagination="3 - 23" refId="ref10976" refString="Chamberlin, R. V. (1941) New western millipeds. Bulletin of the University of Utah, Biological Series, 31 (2), 6, 3 - 23." type="journal article" year="1941">Chamberlin, 1941</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Shear, W. A. &amp; Krejca, J. K." box="[1090,1330,1021,1047]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" pagination="23 - 39" refId="ref11524" refString="Shear, W. A. &amp; Krejca, J. K. (2007) Revalidation of the millipede genus Amplaria Chamberlin 1941 (Diplopoda, Chordeumatida, Striariidae) and description of two new species from caves in Sequoia and Kings Canyon National Parks, California. Zootaxa, 1532 (1), 23 - 39. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1532.1.2" type="journal article" year="2007">Shear &amp; Krejca 2007</bibRefCitation>
, Shear, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">et al.</emphasis>
2017). The second legpair (
<figureCitation box="[498,580,1055,1082]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–14" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1872,1897]" captionTargetBox="[154,1323,153,1811]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1373,151,1855]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 9–14. Striaria columbiana and Amplaria imberbis. Figs. 9, 10. Striaria columbiana. Fig. 9. Left gonopod, mesal view; pcc, posterior lobe of colpocoxite; other labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 10. Right gonopod, lateral view; labels as in Fig. 9. Figs. 11–14. Amplaria imberbis male holotype. Fig. 11. Right gonopod, lateral view; labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 12. Angiocoxite tips of right gonopod, mesal view; labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 13. Legpair 9 of male, anterior view; cp, coxal pore; other labels as in Fig. 8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734462" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734462/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) and other secondary sexual characters including those cited in the description of the genus also conformed to the other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1941" box="[788,894,1090,1116]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Amplaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[788,894,1090,1116]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">Amplaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In redescribing 
<taxonomicName authority="(Chamberlin, 1910)" baseAuthorityName="Chamberlin" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[1085,1432,1090,1117]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Striaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nazinta">
<emphasis box="[1085,1199,1091,1117]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">A. nazinta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Chamberlin, R. V." box="[1215,1424,1090,1116]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" pagination="233 - 262" refId="ref10890" refString="Chamberlin, R. V. (1910) Diplopoda from the western states. Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 3, 233 - 262, pls. XXX-XLIII. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / aesa / 3.4.233" type="journal article" year="1910">Chamberlin, 1910</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Shear, W. A. &amp; Nosler, P. &amp; Marek, P. E." box="[151,362,1125,1151]" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" pagination="233 - 240" refId="ref11657" refString="Shear, W. A., Nosler, P. &amp; Marek, P. E. (2017) The identity of Amplaria nazinta (Chamberlin, 1910): a century-old millipede mystery resolved (Diplopoda, Chordeumatida, Striariidae). Zootaxa, 4311 (2), 233 - 240. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4311.2.4" type="journal article" year="2017">
Shear 
<emphasis box="[223,280,1125,1151]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">et al.</emphasis>
(2017)
</bibRefCitation>
noted that the labral spines of this species were strongly reduced. In all species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1941" box="[1298,1404,1125,1151]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Amplaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1298,1404,1125,1151]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">Amplaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
so far studied, including several awaiting description, the second leg’s (
<figureCitation box="[923,1005,1159,1186]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–14" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1872,1897]" captionTargetBox="[154,1323,153,1811]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1373,151,1855]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 9–14. Striaria columbiana and Amplaria imberbis. Figs. 9, 10. Striaria columbiana. Fig. 9. Left gonopod, mesal view; pcc, posterior lobe of colpocoxite; other labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 10. Right gonopod, lateral view; labels as in Fig. 9. Figs. 11–14. Amplaria imberbis male holotype. Fig. 11. Right gonopod, lateral view; labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 12. Angiocoxite tips of right gonopod, mesal view; labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 13. Legpair 9 of male, anterior view; cp, coxal pore; other labels as in Fig. 8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734462" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734462/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) trochanters bear setae-crowned lobes of varying lengths, and some showed strong development of the sixth crest of the second ring. Since the gonopods (
<figureCitation box="[159,292,1229,1255]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–14" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1872,1897]" captionTargetBox="[154,1323,153,1811]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1373,151,1855]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 9–14. Striaria columbiana and Amplaria imberbis. Figs. 9, 10. Striaria columbiana. Fig. 9. Left gonopod, mesal view; pcc, posterior lobe of colpocoxite; other labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 10. Right gonopod, lateral view; labels as in Fig. 9. Figs. 11–14. Amplaria imberbis male holotype. Fig. 11. Right gonopod, lateral view; labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 12. Angiocoxite tips of right gonopod, mesal view; labels as in Fig. 6. Fig. 13. Legpair 9 of male, anterior view; cp, coxal pore; other labels as in Fig. 8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734462" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734462/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="282">Figs. 11, 12</figureCitation>
) follow the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1941" box="[428,534,1229,1255]" class="Diplopoda" family="Striariidae" genus="Amplaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="7" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
